LEAD B: THE 1/3 RATIO — DEEP ANALYSIS
  Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 ≈ 1/3 universally.
  From Fourier: H = mean + sum of level-2 terms + level-4 terms + ...
  Var(H) = sum_{|S|>0} H_hat(S)^2 (Parseval)
  Mean(H)^2 = H_hat(0)^2
  So Var/Mean^2 = (sum_{|S|>0} H_hat^2) / H_hat(0)^2
  = (non-constant energy) / (constant energy)
  ≈ 0.25/0.75 = 1/3 !!
======================================================================

  n=3:
    E_nonconst / E_0 = 0.7500 / 2.2500 = 0.333333
    Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 = 0.333333
    Match? True
    Close to 1/3? True

  n=4:
    E_nonconst / E_0 = 3.0000 / 9.0000 = 0.333333
    Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 = 0.333333
    Match? True
    Close to 1/3? True

  n=5:
    E_nonconst / E_0 = 17.8125 / 56.2500 = 0.316667
    Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 = 0.316667
    Match? True
    Close to 1/3? True

  *** THEOREM: Var(H)/Mean(H)^2 = E_nonconst/E_0 EXACTLY ***
  This is a Fourier identity (Parseval): Var = sum of non-constant Fourier energies.
  And E_nonconst/E_0 ≈ 1/3 because the level-2 energy is ~25% of total,
  and E_0 is ~75%, giving ratio 25/75 = 1/3.

  WHY IS E_0 ≈ 75%?
  E_0 = mean(H)^2. E_total = mean(H^2). E_0/E_total = mean(H)^2/mean(H^2).
  This is 1/(1 + CV^2) where CV = std/mean.
  If CV^2 = 1/3, then E_0/E_total = 3/4 = 75%. Circular but correct!

